Exploratory Analysis - Between sessions

Akira Banerjee

2023-09-27

Between-session loss-chasing

Players can chase losses between (i.e., across sessions) gambling sessions by re-returning faster following a last losing session and increasing the wagers in the next session following a losing session.

Number of sessions

In this section we account for the total number of sessions played across each involvement level (high and low) groups. We both, plot the distribution of the number of sessions played by the players in each involvement group as well as test the between-group comparison of the number of sessions played across the two groups.

players_with_certain_sessions <- session_descriptive_df %>%
  # divide the total number of sessions into bins
  # note that the scale is transformed so that larger values are compressed
  mutate(n_session_bin = cut(n_sessions, 
                             breaks = c(0:10, (2:10)*10, (2:10)*100, (2:5)*1000)),
         n_session_label = cut(n_sessions, 
                             breaks = c(0:10, (2:10)*10, (2:10)*100, (2:5)*1000),
                             labels = 1:32)
  ) %>%
  # count the number of players with certain numbers of sessions
  count(group_levels, n_session_bin, n_session_label) %>%
  mutate(
    group = factor(group_levels,
                   labels = c("High-Involvement", "Low-Involvement")),
    n_session_label = as.numeric(n_session_label)
  )

Session Stakes

In this section we perform a between-group comparison of the amount of session stakes placed by the players across high- and low-involvement groups.

# compare the high-involvement group and the low-involvement group
sess_stakes_HR <- filter(session_descriptive_df, group_levels == "High-involvement")
sess_stakes_LR <- filter(session_descriptive_df, group_levels == "Low-involvement")

# Independent t-tests
sess_stakes_max_comp    <- TES(sess_stakes_HR$stake_max, sess_stakes_LR$stake_max, paired = FALSE, conf = 0.95)
sess_stakes_min_comp    <- TES(sess_stakes_HR$stake_min, sess_stakes_LR$stake_min, paired = FALSE, conf = 0.95)
sess_stakes_mean_comp   <- TES(sess_stakes_HR$stake_mean, sess_stakes_LR$stake_mean, paired = FALSE, conf = 0.95)
sess_stakes_median_comp <- TES(sess_stakes_HR$stake_median, sess_stakes_LR$stake_median, paired = FALSE, conf = 0.95)

# combine all the above df's togather
stake_comp <- rbind(sess_stakes_max_comp, sess_stakes_min_comp, sess_stakes_mean_comp, sess_stakes_median_comp) %>%
  mutate(comp = c("Maximum stake", "Minimum stake", "Mean stake", "Median stake")) %>%
  select(comp, everything())

comp_formatted <- stake_comp %>%
  mutate(
    across(c(mean_x, sd_x, mean_y, sd_y, diff, lowerCI, upperCI), ~round(.x, digits = 2)),
    across(c(df, t, logBF), ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    across(c(d, g), ~round(.x, digits = 3)))

Session Net wins

In this section we compare the net session wins across the two groups. The net session wins are determined from the net session outcome (which is calculated as follows : session win - session stake). If the net session outcome > 0 then the value corresponds to net session win i.e., net session outcome = net session win.

# compare the high-involvement group and the low-involvement group
net_wins_HR <- filter(session_descriptive_df, group_levels == "High-involvement")
net_wins_LR <- filter(session_descriptive_df, group_levels == "Low-involvement")

# Independent t-tests
net_win_max_comp    <- TES(net_wins_HR$net_outcome_max_win , net_wins_LR$net_outcome_max_win , paired = FALSE, conf = .95) # net max wins
net_win_min_comp    <- TES(net_wins_HR$net_outcome_min_win, net_wins_LR$net_outcome_min_win, paired = FALSE, conf = .95) # net min wins
net_win_mean_comp   <- TES(net_wins_HR$net_outcome_mean_win, net_wins_LR$net_outcome_mean_win, paired = FALSE, conf = .95) # net mean wins
net_win_median_comp <- TES(net_wins_HR$net_outcome_median_win, net_wins_LR$net_outcome_median_win, paired = FALSE, conf = .95) # net median wins

Session Net Losses

In this section we compare the net session losses across the two groups. The net session loss was determined from the net session outcome (which is calculated as follows : session win - session stake). If the net session outcome < 0 then the value corresponds to net session loss i.e., net session outcome = net session loss. Note that net session outcomes < 0 i.e., net session losses were negative values. In order to get the correct magnitude estimates of net session losses for specific variables (e.g., max/min net loss) we have accounted for the absolute values of net session losses.

# compare the high-involvement group and the low-involvement group
net_loss_HR <- filter(session_descriptive_df, group_levels == "High-involvement")
net_loss_LR <- filter(session_descriptive_df, group_levels == "Low-involvement")

# Independent t-tests
net_loss_max_comp    <- TES(net_loss_HR$net_outcome_max_loss , net_loss_LR$net_outcome_max_loss , paired = FALSE, conf = .95) # max net losses
net_loss_min_comp    <- TES(net_loss_HR$net_outcome_min_loss, net_loss_LR$net_outcome_min_loss, paired = FALSE, conf = .95) # min net losses
net_loss_mean_comp   <- TES(net_loss_HR$net_outcome_mean_loss, net_loss_LR$net_outcome_mean_loss, paired = FALSE, conf = .95) # mean losses
net_loss_median_comp <- TES(net_loss_HR$net_outcome_median_loss, net_wins_LR$net_outcome_median_loss, paired = FALSE, conf = .95) # median losses

Combine in one table

# in the manuscript, we present all information in one table
# here we combine the separate tables into one
one_table <- rbind(num_sess_comp, stake_comp, net_win_comp, 
                   net_loss_comp, brk_ev_sess, total_spent_comp)

# for brevity, we do not report results on maximum and minimum
#one_table <- one_table %>%
  #filter(!comp %in% c("Maximum stake", "Minimum stake", "Maximum win",
                     # "Minimum win", "Maximum loss", "Minimum loss"))

# correct the p values for multiple comparisons
one_table$p <- p.adjust(one_table$pt, method = "holm")

# do some formatting
one_table <- one_table %>%
  mutate(
    # rename comp into Parameter
    Parameter = comp,
    # for these variables, keep 1 digit after the decimal point
    across(c(mean_x:t, logBF), ~round(.x, digits = 1)),
    # for effect size g, keep 3 digits after the decimal point
    g = round(g, digits = 3),
    # report p values below .001 as < .001
    p = ifelse(p < .001, "<.001", sprintf("%.3f", round(p, digits = 3))),
    # combine mean and standard deviation for each group
    `High-involvement` = paste0(mean_x, " (", sd_x, ")"),
    `Low-involvement` = paste0(mean_y, " (", sd_y, ")")
    ) %>%
  # delete some redundant variables
  select(-c(comp:sd_y), -pt, -pw, -d, -BF) %>%
  select(Parameter, `High-involvement`, `Low-involvement`, diff, lowerCI, upperCI, df, t, p, logBF, g)

table_final_play_beh <- rempsyc::nice_table(one_table ,
           title = c("Table 2", "Comparison of play behaviour across high and low involvement group"))

Time of re-return

Players may chase losses by re-returning faster following a last losing session as compared to a last winning session. In this set of exploratory analyses we assess if between-session chasing is observed following losing vs.winning sessions via time of re-engagement and whether high-involvement players re-return sooner than low-involvement players.

# load data
session_gap_df <- read_csv(here("data", "processed_data","EDA", "Between_session", "session_gap_df.csv"))

The distribution of the dependent variable - mean session duration is positively skewed so we log transform the mean session duration.

#plot the distribution of the DV

mean_sess_gap_dist_overall <- ggplot(session_gap_df, aes(x = mean_session_gap, fill=group_levels)) +
                          geom_histogram(bins = 150) +
                          # add the title, x and y labels
                          labs(x = "Mean Between-Session Gap (in mins) ",
                               y = "Number of players") #+
                         # geom_density(aes(x = mean_session_gap, after_stat(count)))
  

mean_sess_gap_dist_overall  <- mean_sess_gap_dist_overall  + guides(fill = guide_legend(title="Involvement Level"))
mean_sess_gap_dist_overall 

# save the figure in the fig folder
ggsave("figure/mean_sess_gap_dist_overall.png", mean_sess_gap_dist_overall)
#the distribution is heavily right-skewed and thus not normally distributed
session_gap_df$log_mean_sess_gap <- log(session_gap_df$mean_session_gap)

Mixed ANOVA Model

session_gap_anova <- aov_ez(id = "player_id",
                        dv = "mean_session_gap",
                        between = "group_levels",
                        within = "prev_outcome",
                        transformation = "log",
                        data = session_gap_df,
                        na.rm = TRUE)
session_gap_anova_table <- nice(session_gap_anova)

# format the anova table
session_gap_table <- session_gap_anova_table%>%
  mutate(
    Parameter = "Time to re-return (in mins))",
    Effect = c("Involvement level", 
               "Prior Outcome", "Interaction: Involvement level * Prior Outcome"),
    # remove asterisks from the F values
    `F` = str_remove_all(`F`, "[*]"),
    # remove white space
    `F` = str_trim(`F`),

  mutate(
    Comparison = c("High-Loss vs. High-Win",
                   "Low-Loss vs. Low-Win",
                   "High-Loss vs. Low-Loss",
                   "High-Win vs. Low-Win",
                   "(High-Loss - High-Win) vs. (Low-Loss - Low-Win)"),pt = p.adjust(pt, method = "holm"))

  mutate(
    across(mean_x:upperCI, ~round(.x, digits = 2)),
    across(c(d,g), ~round(.x, digits = 3)),
    t = round(t, digits = 1),
    df = round(df, digits = 1),

    logBF = round(logBF, digits = 2)
  )%>%
  select(Comparison, mean_x:t, p, logBF, g)

Session stake change

# load data
stake_change_df <- read_csv(here("data", "processed_data", "EDA", "Between_session", "stake_df.csv"))

Next we want to investigate if there were if the difference between the stakes placed across - 1.) a.] High-involvement and b.] Low-involvement players (Between-subjects factor) differed within the - 2.) a.] Loss and b.] Win session outcome (Within-subjects factor). The dependent variable is the mean session stake difference between n and n+1 session and the independent variables are the between- and within-subjects factors.

First lets visualize the distribution of the dependent variable - mean session stake

#plot the distribution of the DV
mean_stake_diff_dist <- ggplot(stake_change_df , aes(x = mean_stake, fill = group_levels)) +
                          geom_histogram(bins = 300) +
                    # add the title, x and y labels
                    labs( x = "Session Stake Difference value (in Euro)",
                          y = "Number of players",
                         # color = "Involvement Levels"
                        )# + 
#  facet_grid(group_levels ~ session_outcome)

mean_stake_diff_dist <- mean_stake_diff_dist + guides(fill = guide_legend(title="Involvement Level"))
mean_stake_diff_dist

#the distribution is heavily right-skewed and thus not normally distributed
#there are negative values because we account for a negative and positive difference instead of an absolute difference because we need to know the direction of the difference. A negative difference would mean spent less and a positive difference would mean spent more.

Mixed ANOVA Model

stake_change_anova <- aov_ez(id = "player_id",
                                   dv = "mean_stake",
                                   between = "group_levels",
                                   within = "prev_outcome",
                                   transformation = "log",
                                   data = stake_change_df,
                                   na.rm = TRUE)

stake_change_anova_table <- nice(stake_change_anova)

stake_change_table <- stake_change_anova_table%>%
  mutate(
    Parameter = "Session Wagers (in Euro",
    Effect = c("Involvement level", 
               "Prior Outcome", "Interaction: Involvement level * Prior Outcome"),
    # remove asterisks from the F values
    `F` = str_remove_all(`F`, "[*]"),
    # remove white space
    `F` = str_trim(`F`),
    p = `p.value`
  ) %>%
  #select(Parameter, Effect, df, MSE, `F`, ges, p)
  select(Effect, df, MSE, `F`, ges, p)
